1. **Figma**: Collaborative interface design tool.

column8: The Importance of Revisiting Old Systems
column10:
Hey Candace,

Hope you’ve had a great week 🙌

Before we get started today, I just had a couple of quick
reminders:

* We’re hosting our Autumn Reset workshop (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wre93fvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/owhedkwphwuwrg0g95bq/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2F1dHVtbi1yZXNldC0yMDI1LXdvcmtzaG9wLWNvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi8=
) this Saturday - it’s the perfect chance to reflect on the last
90 days and set yourself up for success for the final 100 days of
2025. This time of year it’s easy to think “I’ll start in
January” but there’s still (almost) 1/3 of the year left and you
can join the workshop to set up a plan for those final 100 days.
You can sign up by clicking here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wre93fvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/z2hvwgo5b7ue3pmp60uz/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2F1dHVtbi1yZXNldC0yMDI1LXdvcmtzaG9wLWNvbmZpcm1hdGlvbi8=
).
* Secondly, in case you missed it last week, we’ve just launched
our second app Momentum (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wre93fvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/3ohphdu374k4mxtp/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL2NyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcy8xOA==
). If you’re looking to set yourself up, improve your consistency
and leverage accountability to improve your personal
productivity, you can check it out here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wre93fvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/3ohphdu374k4mxtp/aHR0cHM6Ly9nby5zcGFya2xlLnNvL21vbWVudHVtL2NyZWF0b3Jub3Rlcy8xOA==
). (And for those of you who are waiting for the Android version,
we’re working on it! It should be launched in the coming weeks).

Anyway, on with today’s email and I actually wanted to use it to
just give a quick update on the channel and talk a little bit
about what I’ve found to be working again for me personally when
it comes to filming content.

And it partly relates to last Friday’s video (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wre93fvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/n2hohquv36l6qmu0/aHR0cHM6Ly95b3V0dS5iZS9nTzBidlRfc21kTQ==
) which is performing really well compared to recent videos. It
was a pleasant surprise to see a 1 out of 10 again - it’s been
quite a while since we’ve had those fireworks and, as much as I
don’t like chasing the numbers, it’s nice to see when a video
really hits 😅 (My YouTube Producer, Becky, actually wrote a
LinkedIn post about it here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.
) if you want to read more about how that video in particular was
created).

But if you’ve watched it, you’ll know that it’s a little bit
different in that we decided to get out of my usual comfort zone
behind my desk and film around various places in Hong Kong. And
this wasn’t just a decision we made on a whim. It was actually an
intentional move to switch things up - not just by changing the
environment but also part of a new routine whereby we’re
dedicating Tuesday as being the only day in the week when I will
be filming.

Why? Well, after reflecting on my filming struggles over the past
few months, I realised that one of the reasons that I’ve been
finding it hard to get consistent is because filming had become
one of those things that I was trying to fit in-between
everything else. And when filming becomes something which ‘fits
into the gaps’ in the calendar, if there aren’t any gaps, filming
doesn’t get done (obvious really 😅).

This was particularly noticeable when we travelled to the UK in
August - we had various family and friend commitments - catching
up with everyone - and so filming was relegated to the bottom of
the list. But this pattern of filming ‘in the gaps’ has been
creeping into production for the past 6-8 months which is partly
because of life events but also because I’d slipped out of the
ideal week schedule that I’d previously crafted where I dedicated
days to filming.

So we’ve now set aside Tuesday as the filming day which means
that Becky’s able to organise the production in/around that core
commitment every week and I know that my one professional
objective that day is to film. And it seems to be working.

Over the past two weeks, we’ve filmed 6/7 videos, we’ve filled
the calendar up for the next 3 weeks and suddenly editing is the
bottleneck rather than me which makes a change. (On that note,
we’re actually looking for a freelance video editor to help with
the YouTube channel, if you’re interested, you can apply here (
https://click.convertkit-mail2.com/o8u2p8v079tqh6wre93fvhq4m9rrriohqe49l/wnh2h6uqwxlx76fl/aHR0cHM6Ly9hbGlhYmRhYWwuY29tL2pvYnMvZnJlZWxhbmNlLXZpZGVvLWVkaXRvci8=
)).

And the thing is, this shouldn’t really be a surprise.

It’s very similar to the setup that I had when I was back in
Cambridge in 2020 (let me know if you were watching at that time
😅) when I used to travel to WeWork every Tuesday, meet with my
General Manager, Angus (who was my only employee at the time),
we’d plan our weekly videos, I’d let them simmer for 24-48hrs,
and then we’d have a filming day on a Thursday.

And that system just worked. We’d regularly film 2, 3, 4 videos
every Thursday, we were publishing 2/3 videos every week which
created a momentum on the channel and that really accelerated our
growth throughout 2020 and into 2021.

I wasn’t trying to fit filming sessions into random days or
trying to split the recording across multiple sessions - I had a
day set aside and that was the day I knew I needed to turn up to
film. And that’s what we’ve returned to now.

You might be wondering why we ever stopped doing that and, to be
honest, I’m not sure. Or rather, there wasn’t anything in
particular but just general business changes, shifting
priorities, calendars getting full, products being
launched…things sometimes just drift without you really noticing.

And part of the reason I’m saying this is because, even with 6
million subscribers, I’m still re-learning lessons from my own
past experiences; I’m still iterating on my systems to optimise
for my new life.

In other words, creating a system around your YouTube channel is
important but it’s not a one-and-done thing - it’s an ongoing
process where you might find yourself circling back to systems
and processes that worked in the past but you’ve just drifted
away from.

Of course, I realise that setting aside a full day to film just
isn’t feasible for everyone with work or family commitments but
it’s less about finding a day and more about being intentional
about your filming schedule and trying to batch record content
rather than filming week-to-week.

In fact, back when I was a doctor and before I had any team
members, batching my content was how I managed to sustain 2/3
videos per week throughout 2018 and 2019. I’d fit the
researching, writing, preparing videos into whatever time I could
find during my shifts but then set aside dedicated time for when
I knew I needed the most energy - the actual filming. And I’d
batch record a series of videos on one particular day every
couple of weeks.

And this is important because it really is easy to slip into the
video-to-video routine and whilst there’s not a specific issue
with that approach, it does lead to this feeling of being on a
hamster wheel with your content and constantly running to keep up
(the whole Red Queen effect) which is just draining over time and
quickly leads to burnout.

I often talk about being consistent with publishing content and
that is important but it’s almost equally important to think
about how you can get consistent with your production. If you can
figure out when you’re most energised and create a routine or
system around that rather than trying to fit filming into the
liminal spaces between everything else in life, consistency in
your output will follow.

I’m sure I’ll need to be reminded of the power of this setup
again in the future - I’m hoping that writing this email will
help reiterate this for me but I hope it serves as a useful

column7: RICE-A: A Prioritization Framework for AI-Driven Features | AI PM Jobs
column9:
View this post on the web at https://marily.substack.com/p/rice-a-a-prioritization-framework

In today’s AI-driven world, prioritizing features for development is a critical challenge. Traditional frameworks like RICE excel at helping teams evaluate feature ideas based on Reach, Impact, Confidence, and Effort. However, when it comes to AI products, the unique challenges of data collection, model training, and deployment require a nuanced approach. I see Product Managers sometimes including these challenges within ‘Effort’ but I don’t believe that this is the right approach.
That’s why I am introducing RICE-A, an enhanced prioritization framework tailored specifically for AI-driven features. RICE-A will help product managers make data-informed decisions, balancing innovation with execution feasibility.
What Is RICE-A?
RICE-A builds on the RICE framework by introducing a fifth factor: AI Complexity (A). This additional layer captures the unique effort required by the AI lifecycle - to design, train, and deploy AI models, ensuring AI-specific challenges are weighted appropriately.
The RICE-A Formula:
Each component evaluates a specific aspect of the feature's feasibility and potential:
Reach: What percentage of your target audience will benefit from this feature?
Impact: How significant is the impact for the target user?
Confidence: How certain are you about the accuracy of your assumptions and ability to deliver?
Effort: What is the engineering effort needed to implement the feature?
AI Complexity (A): What are the data and computational demands for collecting the right dataset, training a robust model, and ensuring scalability?
Why Add "AI Complexity"?
AI features present unique challenges that aren't captured by traditional effort metrics. For example:
Data Challenges: Collecting, cleaning, and labeling high-quality datasets is often a monumental task.
Training Costs: Model training requires substantial computational resources, hyperparameter tuning, and infrastructure setup.
Deployment & Monitoring: AI systems demand post-deployment monitoring, retraining, and bias detection to ensure sustained performance.
How to Use RICE-A
Step 1: Score Each Component
Assign scores to each factor based on your product's context. For example:
Reach: % of users impacted (e.g., 50% of all feature users).
Impact: Use a scale of 1–5 to evaluate the impact of the feature.
Confidence: Evaluate the quality of data and assumptions (e.g., 80% = 0.8).
Effort: Estimated engineering hours, scaled inversely (e.g., 50 hours = score of 0.02).
AI Complexity: Break down model-specific tasks (e.g., data preprocessing, training) into effort scores. I recommend including a 0.5 multiplier for AI complexity. This is because AI-related efforts are typically intensive but should not overshadow general engineering effort unless justified. This way the AI complexity is weighted proportionately and doesn't dominate the scoring unless significant.
Step 2: Calculate the RICE-A Score
Plug your scores into the formula to derive a single priority score. Higher scores indicate features that deliver the most value relative to the effort required.
Step 3: Prioritize Features
Sort your list of potential features by their RICE-A scores. Reevaluate periodically to ensure alignment with team capabilities and business goals.
A Practical Example
Let’s say your team is considering a feature that uses AI to introduce recommendations on Netflix. Here’s how it might score in RICE-A:
You can now determine if it’s worth pursuing and stack rank all proposed AI-powered features which will help you create a roadmap.
Benefits of RICE-A
Clarity on AI-Specific Effort: Highlights the often-hidden complexities of AI projects.
Alignment with Stakeholders: Provides a data-driven way to justify priorities to leadership.
Efficient Resource Allocation: Helps teams focus on high-impact, feasible features.
Alright so RICE-A is a natural evolution of the RICE framework, bridging the gap between traditional prioritization and the unique demands of AI-driven product development. By explicitly accounting for AI complexity, product managers can better evaluate trade-offs, align teams, and drive impactful innovation.
Thoughts?
